Steps Performed – Implementing CORS in Spring Boot
Step 1: Created a Spring Boot Project
Opened Spring Tool Suite (STS).
Created a new Spring Boot project using Spring Initializr.
Added the required dependency:
Spring Web
Step 2: Created a REST Controller
Created a package named controller.
Created a class named ProductController.
Added the @RestController annotation.
Created a REST API using the @GetMapping("/products") annotation.
Step 3: Enabled CORS at the Controller Level
Added the @CrossOrigin annotation above the API method.

Configured the allowed origin as:

@CrossOrigin(origins = "http://localhost:8080")
This allowed only requests coming from http://localhost:8080.
Step 4: Ran the Spring Boot Application
Started the Spring Boot application.
Verified that the embedded Tomcat server started successfully.

The application was accessible on:

http://localhost:9090
Step 5: Tested the REST API
Opened Postman.

Sent a GET request to:

http://localhost:9090/products

Received the response:

Product List
Step 6: Verified Cross-Origin Access

Accessed the REST API from a frontend running on:

http://localhost:8080
Confirmed that the request was allowed because the origin matched the value specified in the @CrossOrigin annotation.
Global CORS Configuration
Step 7: Configured CORS Globally
Opened the main Spring Boot application class (DemoApplication.java).
Created a WebMvcConfigurer bean.
Overrode the addCorsMappings() method.

Configured CORS globally using:

registry.addMapping("/products")
        .allowedOrigins("http://localhost:8080");
Step 8: Applied CORS to All APIs

Updated the mapping:

registry.addMapping("/**")
This enabled CORS support for all REST endpoints in the application.
Step 9: Allowed Multiple Origins

Configured multiple frontend applications to access the backend:

.allowedOrigins(
    "http://localhost:8080",
    "http://localhost:3000"
)
Step 10: Allowed HTTP Methods

Configured the supported HTTP methods:

.allowedMethods(
    "GET",
    "POST",
    "PUT",
    "DELETE"
)
Step 11: Allowed Request Headers

Configured the application to accept all request headers:

.allowedHeaders("*")
Step 12: Tested the Application
Restarted the Spring Boot application.
Verified that the frontend could successfully communicate with the backend without any CORS errors.
Confirmed the APIs were working correctly using both a web application and Postman.
